{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17640959","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17640959"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:21:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:21:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17852"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17852","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17852"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10566"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78563"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10566","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10566"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17852"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63905"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24635"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24638"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78563","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78563"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EGlycogen phosphorylase is a key enzyme in muscle metabolism that catalyses the breakdown of glycogen stores. Its activity is tightly regulated by several metabolic signals.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the regulation of glycogen phosphorylase in skeletal muscle?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Calcium ions activate the enzyme","Glucose-6-phosphate stimulates the enzyme","AMP suppresses enzyme activity","ATP enhances enzyme activity","The enzyme lacks allosteric regulation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcium ions activate the enzyme\u003C/strong\u003E in skeletal muscle cells. This activation occurs during muscle contraction when calcium is released from the sarcoplasmic reticulum, signalling the need for increased energy production through glycogen breakdown.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlucose-6-phosphate stimulates the enzyme\u003C/strong\u003E - Glucose-6-phosphate actually inhibits glycogen phosphorylase as it indicates sufficient glucose availability\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAMP suppresses enzyme activity\u003C/strong\u003E - AMP activates glycogen phosphorylase, signalling low energy status and the need for glycogen breakdown\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EATP enhances enzyme activity\u003C/strong\u003E - ATP inhibits glycogen phosphorylase when cellular energy levels are high\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe enzyme lacks allosteric regulation\u003C/strong\u003E - Glycogen phosphorylase is extensively regulated by allosteric mechanisms including AMP, ATP, glucose-6-phosphate and calcium ions\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese regulatory mechanisms ensure that glycogen breakdown is precisely matched to muscle energy demands during rest and exercise.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Glycogen phosphorylase breaks down glycogen into glucose-1-phosphate to provide energy during muscle contraction.","Glycogen phosphorylase is inhibited by glucose-6-phosphate and ATP, which signal high cellular energy status.","Glycogen phosphorylase is activated by AMP and calcium ions, which indicate low energy status or muscle contraction."],"references":["Bender, D. A., \u0026 Cunningham, S. M. (2021). Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press","Salway, J. G. (2016). Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Chandel NS. Carbohydrate Metabolism. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2021 Jan 4;13(1):a040568. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a040568. PMID: 33397651; PMCID: PMC7778149"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63905"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17852"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63905","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63905"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-11T15:25:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-11T15:26:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10566"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78563"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4931"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Musculoskeletal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024